# FVT tests

The kserve functional verification test are stored in kserve/test/e2e. Despite the e2e folder name, we call these tests fvt because they are not truly “end to end” for the product in ODH or downstream.

# Configuration

The set of fvt tests that are run as part of openshift CI are defined in [https://github.com/openshift/release/blob/master/ci-operator/config/opendatahub-io/kserve/opendatahub-io-kserve-master.yaml](https://github.com/openshift/release/blob/master/ci-operator/config/opendatahub-io/kserve/opendatahub-io-kserve-master.yaml)

The list of pytest markers available are defined in [https://github.com/kserve/kserve/blob/master/test/e2e/pytest.ini](https://github.com/kserve/kserve/blob/master/test/e2e/pytest.ini)

# Running Locally

1. Set up a new cluster
   1. Start with a brand new cluster (See [HOWTO: RHOAI engineering - ROSA-hosted install guide](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1DQgZwj0GjCASfolFeAMXQQ1ZFRvFUp_4p1ZI_GDE42c/edit?usp=sharing))
   2. A brand new cluster is highly recommended because the e2e setup does not play well with existing objects.
   3. Login to the cluster in your terminal
2. \[Optional\] Build images

```
export KO_DOCKER_REPO=quay.io/<your_username>
export TAG=master
```

#### Sklearn

```
make docker-build-sklearn git@github.com:opendatahub-io/kserve.git
docker tag ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/sklearnserver
 ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-sklearn:${TAG}
docker push ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-sklearn:${TAG}
export SKLEARN_IMAGE=${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-sklearn:${TAG}
```

#### Storage Initializer

```
make docker-build-storageInitializer
docker tag ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/storage-initializer ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-storage-initializer:${TAG}
docker push ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-storage-initializer:${TAG}
export STORAGE_INITIALIZER_IMAGE=${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-storage-initializer:${TAG}
```

#### Kserve agent

```
make docker-build-agent
docker tag ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/agent ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-agent:${TAG}
docker push ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-agent:${TAG}
export KSERVE_AGENT_IMAGE=${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-agent:${TAG}
```

#### Kserve router

```
make docker-build-router
docker tag ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/router $ {KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-router:${TAG}
docker push ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-router:${TAG}
export KSERVE_ROUTER_IMAGE=${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-router:${TAG}
```

#### Kserve controller

```
make docker-build
docker tag docker.io/library/kserve-controller:latest ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-controller:${TAG}
docker push ${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-controller:${TAG}
export KSERVE_CONTROLLER_IMAGE=${KO_DOCKER_REPO}/kserve-controller:${TAG}
```

3. Install dependencies

   1. Note: (make sure you do not have a virtual env already activated \- I had issues with this installing correctly with a conda environment active)

   $ ./test/scripts/gh-actions/setup-poetry.sh

   $ cd python/kserve

   $ poetry shell

   $ poetry install \--with test

4. Set environment variables

**NOTE** To build kserve images `$ export BUILD_KSERVE_IMAGES=true`

1.  `$ export RUNNING_LOCAL=true`
2.  For Graph tests:  
    `$ export BUILD_GRAPH_IMAGES=true` will build images, false, to not build images, defaults to true  
    `$ export QUAY_REPO=quay.io/<your_username>` to push images to quay  
    `$ export BUILDER=podman` to use podman BUILDER=docker to use docker, defaults to docker  
    `$ export ERROR_404_ISVC_IMAGE=$QUAY_REPO/kserve/error-404-isvc:latest`  
    `$ export SUCCESS_200_ISVC_IMAGE=$QUAY_REPO/kserve/success-200-isvc:latest`

3.  Run fvt tests

    1.  Run the e2e test script (includes setup commands inside)

    $ cd ../../

    $ ./test/scripts/openshift-ci/run-e2e-tests.sh \<marker\>

Ex: $ SETUP_E2E=true ./test/scripts/openshift-ci/run-e2e-tests.sh predictor

2. Note: If you’re re-running this script a lot, set [SETUP_E2E](https://github.com/opendatahub-io/kserve/blob/master/test/scripts/openshift-ci/run-e2e-tests.sh#L24)\=false \-\> most commands from that script do not like being run multiple times

## Debugging e2e tests

### Debugging Individual Tests

You can run an individual test by changing the pytest call in _test/scripts/gh-actions/run-e2e-tests.sh_ to something like  
$ pytest predictor/test_canary.py::test_canary_rollout \--ignore=qpext \--log-cli-level=DEBUG \-n $PARALLELISM \--dist worksteal

### Debugging CI

Access the cluster linked in the test logs from github (see the “Using namespace …” line)  
![][image1]  
Wait until the e2e-\<test\> pod starts running  
Use terminal in e2e-\<test\> pod:  
Get the credentials for the cluster:  
$ cat /tmp/secret/kubeconfig  
On your own terminal:  
 $ vim kubeconfig \# paste details here  
 $ export KUBECONFIG=kubeconfig \# this logs you in  
And then run whatever debugging commands you need

- Note: The kserve namespace will have the kserve and ODH controller manager pods
